<section xml:id="syllabus" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Course outline</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Students sometimes come into a math class with expectations
      based on their previous experiences and general attitudes in our
      society.  Here are some important facts that inform the way our
      class will be structured.

      <ul>
        <li><title>Math is social</title>
        <p>
          Math is social: Popular culture loves
          stories about a solitary genius who works for years in
          isolation.  In fact, most professional mathematicians work
          closely with others and learn new ideas by talking with one
          another.  This will be a feature of our class.  One of your best
          resources will be your fellow classmates so I will help you get
          to know one another and learn to talk about mathematics.  Not
          only will this help you learn math, but you'll find it to be a
          lot more fun.
        </p>
        </li>
        
        <li><title>We learn by doing</title>
        <p>
          I watched a lot of the NBA playoffs this year (Yay,
          Thunder!), but I still can't make free throws.  The best way
          to learn anything is to do it.  This means that the majority
          of time in our class meetings will be devoted to students
          working through activities with their classmates (math is
          social, right?).  This gives me a chance to get to know all
          of you as learners of math and to provide better feedback
          based on your understanding.
        </p>
        </li>

        <li><title>You belong in this class</title>
        <p>
          Sometimes students can feel anxious in their math class.
          Have other students already had calculus?  Does everyone
          remember everything from their high school math classes?
          Does everyone already know everyone else except me?  These
          are pretty natural concerns but please know that I will do
          my best to get to know you and work with you with complete
          acceptance of your prior experiences.
        </p>
        </li>

        <li><title>Math makes sense</title>
        <p>
          Math makes sense: Based on your previous math courses, you
          may think that the point of math is to get a "right" answer
          as fast as you can using some algorithm that no one really
          understands.  Nope.  Mathematics is a framework for making
          sense of our world, and our goal in this class is to develop
          your ability to think mathematically and to express your
          ideas clearly.  A former student said, <q>Math is a lot easier
          when you think about what it means.</q>
        </p>
        </li>

        <li><title>I want you to succeed</title>
        <p>
          The most satisfying part of my job is seeing my students
          grow as learners of mathematics and watching their
          confidence grow.  I have high expectations of you in this
          course, but I will also provide you with the support that
          you need to reach those expectations.  I am always
          interested in hearing about your experience, whether you are
          feeling frustrated or whether you want to share some recent
          success, and what kind of help you need from me.
        </p>
        </li>

        <li><title>What I expect of you</title>
        <p>
          I've described some things above that I will provide you.
          Because learning is a partnership, I also expect some things
          from you because they will help you be successful.
        </p>

        <p>
          Be open to new experiences and new people.  Share freely
          with one another and accept the contributions of your
          classmates with gratitude.
        </p>

        <p>
          Be willing to accept that you may not understand everything
          when you first see it but that I believe in your ability to
          work with me and your classmates to arrive at a deep
          understanding of mathematics.
        </p>

        <p>
          Stay focused when working for this class.  You may not pay
          monetarily to use social media, but you pay with your
          attention, which is one of your most valuable resources.
          Checking your phone regularly disrupts your concentration
          and significantly detracts from your learning.  This is why
          the people in Silicon Valley who create this technology
          don't let their kids use it.  You may have a legitimate need
          to check your notifications during class, but you should
          otherwise be able to keep your phone in your pack for the 50
          minutes that we meet.
        </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Equity</title>
      <p>
        We live in a world where not all groups of people are always
        treated fairly.  Please know that I am fully committed to
        fairness and equity and that in all aspects of this course I
        will not tolerate language, ideas, or behaviors that are
        hostile to groups of people, such as racism, sexism,
        homophobia, transphobia, and xenophobia.  In new situations,
        people are sometimes uncertain about what language and ideas
        could be hostile or offensive.  If you feel this way, I am
        more than willing to discuss these issues with you
        privately. I will always treat these conversations
        confidentially, with respect, and without judgment.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Land acknowledgment</title>
      <p>
        Grand Valley State University is settled on the unceded
        territory of the Anishinaabeg--Three Fires Confederacy: the
        Ojibwe, Odawa, and Potawatomi.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </introduction>

