  <!-- Use paragraphs to break apart subsections -->
    <paragraphs>
      <title>What to call me</title>
      <p> You may address me as
      “Dr. Austin” or “Professor Austin”, and I prefer the pronouns
      “he” and “him”.  Please be respectful of your instructors and
      learn how they wish to be addressed.  “Professor” is more
      appropriate than, say, “Mr.” or “Mrs.” but just ask if you ever
      feel uncertain.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Office Hours</title>
      <p> Office hours are times that I am guaranteed to be available
      to you, and you are encouraged to stop by.  Sometimes students
      want to talk about something in the course that is challenging
      or intriguing to them.  But other times, students want to talk
      about a wide variety of other things: resources they can take
      advantage of, career opportunities, some current event, or what
      made me want to be a math professor at Grand Valley.  This is
      time for you, and I’m happy to talk with you about whatever is
      on your mind.
      </p>
      <p>
        It’s hard for me to find a time to hold office hours when all
        my students are available.  I’m flexible and can arrange to
        meet with you at another time, if that works better for you.
        We could also meet by Zoom, if you’re not on campus.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>AI Policy</title>
      <p>This one-word policy is simple: don’t.  Please don’t use
      generative AI to complete any assignments or to check your work
      in this course.  As full disclosure, I will tell you that I use
      AI as part of a research project to develop a large-language
      model that will translate math research papers into braille for
      blind readers.  This task is very different from actually
      learning mathematics, which is your job in this class.  You may
      think:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            “I will be using AI in my career.”  With the current state
            of AI, you won’t be using it to learn new ways of
            thinking, like we’re trying to do in our course.  For one,
            it’s not particularly good at doing mathematics, and it
            won’t help you develop an understanding of mathematics.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>“I only use it to check my work when I don’t feel totally
          confident.”  I am part of a math education research study
          that investigates how students learn math from textbooks.
          Interviews with students clearly show how using AI causes
          students to become less confident over time since they come
          to trust what comes from AI more than they trust their own
          work.  Learning will be challenging and facing challenges
          requires you to have the confidence that you can do it.
          Please don’t surrender the trust that you have in your own
          abilities.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      </p>

      <p>
        One research study, among others, is described here:
        <url href="https://www.nytimes.com/2025/07/03/opinion/aritificial-intelligence-education.html?unlocked_article_code=1.d08.sztp.9zECXshpy_dr=url-share">
          <em>Are We Really Willing to Become Dumber?</em>
        </url>
      </p>

      <p>
        Or as ChatGPT said when asked to translate this policy into
        pirate: “The seas of AI be treacherous and will dull yer
        skills. Ye’ll learn by yer own hand, not by a talking parrot
        spitting answers.”
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Phone policy</title>
      <p>
        During our class meetings, please keep your phone stored with
        your belongings and away from your work space, unless you have
        an exceptional situation such as concern for a friend or
        family member.  We live in an age where your attention is
        being monetized by others, and it is not readily apparent the
        price that you are paying.  An overwhelming amount of
        research, however, plainly shows how disruptive this
        technology is to your learning.
        <url href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/26/style/phones-children-silicon-valley.html?unlocked_article_code=1.dk8.6ygB.2TOc7QaMEx3N=url-share">
          “On the scale between candy
          and crack cocaine, it’s closer to crack cocaine,” Mr. Anderson
          [former editor of Wired magazine] said of screens.
        </url>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Technology</title>
      <p>If you have a laptop/tablet/Chromebook, please bring it to
      class.  We will use free, online computational tools such as
      Sage and Desmos.  These tools are superior to a traditional
      calculator so you don’t need to buy a calculator for this
      course.  If you already have a calculator, you are welcome to
      use it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Communication</title>
      <p>I will be posting assignments, activities, and other relevant
      information on our course Blackboard page. I will also be
      communicating with you frequently through email. Please make
      sure that you check your Grand Valley email on a daily basis.
      Please don’t send messages to me through Blackboard’s messaging
      system because I am unlikely to see them in a timely fashion.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    
  </subsection>

  <!-- Other subsections for larger dividers -->
  <subsection xml:id="sec-assessments">
    <title>About MTH 204</title>

    <p>
      <alert>MTH 204</alert> is our first semester course in linear
      algebra.  You may find that linear algebra is a little different
      than some of the other math courses you have taken up to this
      point, and I think you’re going to enjoy it a lot.  Roughly
      speaking, we have three overarching goals.  First, we’d like you
      to learn how to reason about important mathematical concepts and
      to express your reasoning clearly and precisely.  Second, linear
      algebra is shaping our society in profound ways, and we’d like
      you to understand this and to see the powerful ways in which
      mathematics is applied in the world around us.  Finally, the
      mathematician Carl Cowen said that “no significant use of linear
      algebra happens without a computer” so we’ll be developing our
      ability to deploy linear algebraic thinking to solve realistic
      problems using a computer.
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>
        Catalog Description​ of MTH 204, Linear Algebra I
      </title>
      <p>
        <em>
        An introduction to systems of linear equations emphasizing
        conceptual understanding and computational thinking. Primary
        topics include solutions to linear systems, vector and matrix
        algebra, span and linear independence, bases, eigenvectors,
        and eigenvalues. Applications will be integrated throughout
        the course. Offered fall and winter semesters. Prerequisites:
        MTH 122 and MTH 123; or MTH 124; or assignment through Grand
        Valley math placement.”
        </em>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Course Content</title>
      <p>We will study all or nearly all of the material in the first
      four chapters of our textbook, <em>Understanding Linear Algebra.</em>
      Your goal should be, as part of our ongoing work together, to
      read the text itself and ask questions as needed.  Preview
      Activities will normally be assigned for credit (based on effort
      and completeness) as part of your Daily Prep Assignments; the
      other activities in the text will be a central focus of our
      in-class discussions and work, and it’s your responsibility
      (with lots of support from your instructor and one another) to
      make sure you understand them and work through them fully.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Prerequisites</title>
      <p>​ MTH 122/123 or MTH 124 or GV placement.  As you’ll see, this
      course doesn’t rely on prerequisites as much as your calculus
      class would, but there are some times when you’ll need to have a
      working knowledge of important concepts from algebra and
      trigonometry.  I'm willing to help you if you feel rusty with a
      few of these ideas, but you are responsible for making sure you
      have a good understanding of the prerequisite knowledge
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Learning Objectives</title>

      <p>After successful completion of this course, you will
      be able to:
        <ul>
          <li><p>Analyze systems of linear equations and describe
          their solution spaces.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>Describe how the pivot positions of an augmented
          matrix influence the nature of the solution space to a
          linear system.</p></li>
          <li><p>Demonstrate algebraic and geometric fluency with
          vectors.</p></li>
          <li><p>Interpret questions about linear systems as questions
          about linear combinations of vectors.</p></li>
          <li><p>Describe the concept of span of a set of vectors and
          apply it to determine the span of a set of vectors.</p></li>
          <li><p>Describe the concept of linear independence of a set
          of vectors and apply it to determine whether a set of
          vectors is linearly independent.</p></li>
          <li><p>Interpret matrix transformations as functions defined
          through matrix multiplication and create specific matrix
          transformations to perform geometric operations.</p></li>
          <li><p>Calculate matrix sums, products, and multiples by
          scalar, and recognize matrix products as arising from
          composing matrix transformations.</p></li>
          <li><p>Recognize a basis for R n and use the coordinate
          system it defines to solve problems.</p></li>
          <li><p>Recognize an invertible matrix and find its
          inverse.</p></li>
          <li><p>Apply one of several algorithms for finding the
          determinant of a matrix, and use the determinant to
          determine if a matrix is invertible. </p></li>
          <li><p>State the definition and intuitive meaning of an
          eigenvalue-eigenvector pair of a square matrix.</p></li>
          <li><p>Apply a conceptual understanding of linear systems to
          find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a square
          matrix.</p></li>
          <li><p>Demonstrate how the theory of eigenvalues and
          eigenvectors is used to solve problems in dynamical
          systems.</p></li>
          <li><p>Use computer algebra technology as a tool to solve
          important problems in linear algebra.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Assessment and how grades will be determined</title>

    <p>There will be several ways in which you will be assessed in
    this course and which will contribute to your final grade.

    <dl>
      <li><title>Daily prep 10%</title>
      <p>
        Before most class meetings, you will
        be asked to do some work to help prepare for our time together
        in class.  This will often involve working a few short
        problems and providing me with feedback on your preparation.
        These will be graded according to the effort you have put into
        them rather than correctness.
      </p>
      </li>
      <li><title>WebWork 15%</title>
      <p>
        WeBWork is a free online homework system that you will use
        regularly to complete assignments that provide an opportunity
        for you to practice important skills required for success in
        this course.  Webwork provides immediate feedback on your work
        as well as the chance to attempt problems multiple times.
      </p>
      </li>
      <li><title>Learning targets 20%</title>
      <p>
        We will have weekly proficiency
        quizzes addressing a set of
        <xref ref="targets" text="custom">
        Proficiency Learning Targets
        </xref> that
        measure your understanding of certain essential skills you
        need to build a deep understanding of linear algebra.  Since
        this is an important part of the course, more details are
        provided later in this document.
      </p>
      </li>
      <li><title>Written homework 20%</title>
      <p>
        You will have written homework assignments roughly every week.
        The assigned problems will ask you to use the skills assessed
        in the Proficiency Learning Targets as you solve multi-part,
        large-scale problems.  You will be expected to write carefully
        about your work, including justifications of any techniques
        you have used and a summary of your results and conclusions.
        Each problem will be graded on a four-point scale: Exemplary
        (“E”) is 4 points, Satisfactory (“S”) is 3, and Not Yet (“NY”)
        is 0.
      </p>
      </li>

      <li><title>Labs 15%</title>
      <p>About every other week, you’ll start a
        lab or activity in class that you’ll complete and write up
        outside of class for a formal grade; normally these will be
        done in groups of two and assigned a single group grade.
      </p>
      </li>

      <li><title>Final exam 20%</title>
      <p>
        The comprehensive final exam will consist of
        questions that address big-picture ideas in the course, and
        your work on those problems will constitute 20% of your
        semester grade.  More information about the final will be
        available later in the semester.
      </p>
      </li>
    </dl>
    </p>

    <p>Your final grade will be determined on the following scale,
    which is fairly typical at Grand Valley:</p>

