  <subsection>
    <title>Proficiency quizzes</title>

    <p>This course has a set of
    <xref ref="targets" text="custom">
    learning targets
    </xref> that are intended to
    focus your attention on specific skills you should acquire to
    develop a deep understanding of linear algebra.  Here are some
    things to know about why this is an important part of the course.

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Learning is a process. You will not be penalized if you don't
          demonstrate proficiency in a skill the first time, but you are
          expected to do so eventually.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Frequent  assessment is good for learning.  Think of these
          quizzes as a tool for learning rather than   just
          assessment---studies show that retrieval of information
          makes it easier to recall that information later. This is
          called “the testing effect.''
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Keeping up with course material is important.  These quizzes
          will be one way of informing both you and me about your
          progress in the course.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Knowing the basics well is crucial for tackling more
          in-depth problems. These targets were chosen because they
          are fundamental so you should think of them as building
          blocks.  You will have time to practice these skills before,
          during, and after class, but we will also spend class time
          using them to tackle substantial problems.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
    Here are the nuts and bolts of how it works.

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Each Thursday, we will have an in-class quiz that assesses some of
          these skills, which will be announced in advance.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Each skill will be graded on a four-point scale: “E'' for
          “Exemplary'' is four points, “S” for “Satisfactory is three
          points, and “NY'' for “not yet'' is zero points To earn an
          “E,'' your solution needs to show all work and explanations,
          use correct notation, and arrive at a correct answer. In
          short, your work should be close to perfect.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If you did not successfully complete a learning target, you
          can try again next week.  I won't provide a lot of feedback
          because it's very helpful for you to learn to assess your
          work independently of me.  I am happy to talk with you about
          any of your work on the quizzes though.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Since you have multiple attempts on each target, there will
        be no makeup quizzes.</p>
      </li>
      <li><p>Each target will appear on two quizzes.</p></li>
      <li><p>If you still haven't successfully completed a target
      after your second attempt, you are welcome to talk with me about
      it during office hours (or another agreed upon time) within one
      week of the second attempt, and you can have another
      attempt.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Submitting work</title>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Submitting graded work</title>

      <p>
        Make sure that your written homework is prepared neatly and
        well organized so that it's easy to follow.  There should be
        at least two phases to preparing your homework assignments:
        (1) solving the assigned problems and (2) writing up your
        solutions and editing.  Be sure to keep them separate.  If you
        are crossing out portions of your work or including arrows
        pointing to your next steps, you are combining the two phases
        and need to start the writing phase again once you've got a
        better understanding of the problem.  Please include the
        problems in the order in which they are assigned.  Make sure
        your name is clearly indicated.
      </p>

      <p>
        Through our work in class and other things like written
        homework, we will be building from the ground up an
        understanding of linear algebra.  In preparing your homework,
        you should only use results that we have developed in our
        class rather than something that shows up in an internet
        search that may be technically correct but not consistent with
        the framework that we have developed.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Late work</title>
      <p>
        While assignments will always have due dates, I recognize that
        life happens and that you don’t owe me an explanation when it
        does.  Throughout the semester, you are allowed to submit an
        assignment late on three occasions provided you write to me
        beforehand and let me know when you’ll get it to me.  Please
        note that this policy does not apply to learning target
        quizzes.  If you are habitually having a hard time handing
        things in on time, please come and talk with me.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Expectations</title>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Four basic expectations will serve you well in the course:
          <ol>
            <li><p>take responsibility for your own learning</p></li>
            <li><p>attend to details and follow directions</p></li>
            <li><p>seek help when you need support</p></li>
            <li><p>keep a careful written record of all your work</p></li>
          </ol>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>I encourage you to focus your work in MTH 204 on <em>making
          sense and understanding,</em> not on answers or memorization or
          blindly repeating algorithms.  It is more important than
          ever to be able to solve non-routine problems and be
          confident in attacking new ideas.  If you work to make sense
          of ideas, you will be able to think creatively in new ways.
          If you can communicate these ideas to others, you will be
          able to really demonstrate that understanding. These skills
          are far more valuable to your future than any particular
          content you can learn in MTH 204.  As a former student said:
          “linear algebra just makes sense!” (Alexis - the student who
          said that - now holds a PhD in mathematics and works in data
          science and machine learning.)</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><em>Work hard.</em>  This is a 3-credit course, which carries an
          expectation of 6-9 hours of work each week outside of class.
          You will find that things come more easily if you work a
          little bit every day rather than planning a long study
          session before a due date.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><em>Attend each class meeting.</em> Attendance is
          expected and critical to your success, and you will be
          missed if you are absent.  Please be on time to class.
          Showing up is a key to success in all aspects of life.  At
          the same time, I realize that it may be necessary for you to
          miss some class meetings due to work, family commitments,
          and so forth.  In that case, let me know of your absence,
          and we can come up with a plan to help you stay
          up-to-date.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><em>Stay off of social media during class and while
          studying.</em>
          Arguably the most valuable commodity we each possess is our
          attention.  Instagram, SnapChat, TikTok and other apps know
          this, and they were designed (designed by engineers and
          psychologists) to be addictive and persuasive.  If you have
          any of these apps open during class or when you are
          committed to studying, you are guaranteed to be distracted.
          I strongly encourage you to dedicate time free from social
          media distractions so that you can think as clearly as
          possible about the ideas in our course.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><em>Seek help.</em> You have three main resources for
          support with mathematical ideas: (1) office hours or an
          individual appointment with me, (2) your peers in class, and
          (3) the GVSU Math Center.  Be honest with yourself and ask,
          “Do I really understand this?”  If not, find someone who
          does and discuss the ideas with them.</p>

          <p>GVSU’s (free) Math Tutoring Center is offering both
          in-person and virtual tutoring this semester.  More
          information is available here
          http://gvsu.edu/tutoring/math/.  This is a great resource,
          and I encourage you to take advantage of it.</p>

          <p>GVSU’s (free) Math Tutoring Center is offering both
          in-person and virtual tutoring this semester.  More
          information is available here
          http://gvsu.edu/tutoring/math/.  This is a great resource,
          and I encourage you to take advantage of it.</p>

          <p> You may also need help with other aspects of life that
          go beyond mathematics.  If you have special needs because of
          learning, physical, or other disabilities, please contact
          Student Accessibility Resources.  They will help arrange
          accommodations; please inform me of any ways I can be
          supportive.  If you have difficulty affording groceries or
          accessing sufficient food to eat every day, or if you lack a
          safe and stable place to live, I encourage you to visit
          Replenish, a food and living resource for GVSU students. If
          you are comfortable doing so, you are welcome to speak with
          me about your circumstances so that I can advocate for you
          and to connect you with other campus resources.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li><p><em>Be a student of honesty and integrity.</em>  The
        whole point 
        of any course is to learn a lot.  Strive to make your entire
        mindset focused on building understanding and making sense of
        key ideas, and great things will follow.  The structure of
        this course is designed to provide you with alternatives to
        cheating or plagiarism.  With most aspects of this course, you
        can submit your best effort and know that you’ll have
        additional opportunities to correct any misunderstandings and
        grow as a learner.</p></li>

        <li>
          <p><em>Key dates</em>

          <dl>
            <li><title>January 16</title>
	    <p>Last Day to Add or Drop (5pm) </p></li>
            <li><title>February 6</title>
